Ok so, do you know what the sum of the angles in any quadrilateral is?
A quadrilateral is any four sided shape, so like a square, rectangle, parallelogram or kite, which this one is
and the angles inside a quadrilateral always add up to 360 degrees
we know that two of the angle in this quadrilateral are 150 and 60 degrees
if we take those angles away from 360, then that will tell us how much is left for the other two angles
So the other two angles together add up to 150 degrees
Now, those little lines on the side of the kite means that the two shorter sides are both the same length, and the two longer sides are both the same length
which means that a kite is symmetrical - we can chop it in half and the two sides are mirror images of each other
in this case, we could draw a line of symmetry horizontally across the kite, going through the angles of 150 and 60 degrees
So what that also tells us, is that the angle p and the angle that hasn't been labelled are the same - because the kite is symmetrical
so together those two angles add up to 150 degrees and they're both the same
which means we can divide 150 in half to work out how many degrees each angle is
so both p and the other angle that isn't labelled are 75 degrees each
